

# SVM on cancer dataset

**Machine Learning Classification :**

The goal of this study was to implement a python classification model.

To do so we decided to use a cancer database. The classification problem is there to know if the tumor is Benign (target = 0) or Malignant (target = 1). The features given here are:

   #  Attribute                     Domain

   -- -----------------------------------------

   1. Sample code number            id number

   2. Clump Thickness               1 - 10

   3. Uniformity of Cell Size       1 - 10

   4. Uniformity of Cell Shape      1 - 10

   5. Marginal Adhesion             1 - 10

   6. Single Epithelial Cell Size   1 - 10

   7. Bare Nuclei                   1 - 10

   8. Bland Chromatin               1 - 10

   9. Normal Nucleoli               1 - 10

  10. Mitoses                       1 - 10

  11. Class:                        (0 for benign, 1 for malignant)

After choosing our database, we needed to clear some of the data:

- We renamed the target class and changed its values from 2/4 to 0/1
- We removed some input (16 of them) because they were missing data ( an ? was in some columns)

We then wrote our python algorithm. We selected the tools we were going to use and imported them in Python. We used Pandas and Numpy for datasets. The sklearn library itself contains our verifying tools but also the SVN model we used on our data.

For the first approach we arbitraty choose 2 features to be the one we modeled on our representation. We then plotted the result of our SVN model. Using the R and R2 score and looking at the prediction compared to the actual result we were then able to evaluate our model:



**Set 1, Features : Clump Thickness, Uniformity of Cell size :**

Gamma = 0.8

| Model/ Score | **R** | **R2** | **F1** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Linear** | 0.948905109489 | 0.779540229885 | 0.95 |
| **RBF** | 0.92700729927 | 0.685057471264 | 0.93 |
| **Polynomial** | 0.934306569343 | 0.716551724138 | 0.93 |

<img src="./Files/Images/svm.png" alt="test" height="300" width="700"> 

- Selecting the first 2 featured gave us aproximatly 0.7 on the R score and 0.9 on the R2 score. That means our model are good to guess to predict but can be improved (1 being perfection but also risk to be too specific).
- Gamma was chosen here to be 0.8 because it was the best we found to maximize our score without overfitting. For instance with gamma = 10 the RBF model is way to specialized on our set : ![](data:image/*;base64,) )



In order to improve our model we then decided to do another model which would use all of the features given by our dataset. That also means we could not plot it since it is a 10D matrix. So to evaluate it we used the same evaluation as before.

**Set 2, Features : All**

Gamma = 0.8

| Model/ Score | **R** | **R2** | **F1** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Linear** | 1.0 | 1.0 | 1.0 |
| **RBF** | 0.905109489051 | 0.590574712644 | 0.91 |
| **Polynomial** | 0.992700729927 | 0.968505747126 | 0.99 |



- As we can see our score are really better, even at 1 for the linear model (we predicted 100% of our prediction set).
- Nonetheless RBF score reduced a bit

In conclusion we can see that adding all the features to our model improved our prediction on our models, but we also saw that it did not improved ALL the models which means we have to choose intelligibly. On the other hand improving our model can lead to over fitting on a dataset so we have to well test and verify our results.
